snippet.textDisplay:
Hi Dr Mike, I'm a fan of yours. My junior and senior year roommate from college is a nursing major and he turned me onto your channel. I have a question about hygiene. Would you recommend hot showers or cold ones? Not like scalding hot, but like comfortably warm that you don't want to leave anytime soon (especially if it's early in the morning and you're cold). And for cold showers like the ones where you have to psyche yourself into it but can't stay in for more than like a minute or so after rinsing, shampoo/soaping, and getting the soap off.
Also side note, my mom, who I've recently recommended your channel too, works as a physician at a university and she says when you shower, you don't need to put soap on everywhere. She says you just need to wash your face, pits, hands, feet, and where the sun don't shine. Anywhere else, the soap is unnecessary and actually dries you out. Obviously I trust her bc she's a doctor and my mom, but I'm curious what your thoughts on that are.
Have a great day!

snippet.textDisplay: Firstly as a lifeguard, do NOT do chest compressions just because someone is unconscious and not breathing. They need to not be breathing and have no heart rate. If you don’t know how to check their heart rate then just learn how to.
